PLEASE READ BEFORE COMMENTING! I posted this yesterday to tiktok and I was really surprised at how upset this made people in the comments. Usually on my videos the comments are about 95% positive and 5% people who have feedback or criticism or who are just mad. But on this video it was about 90% people who were upset by what they perceived to be the message. They seemed to think that the message being conveyed is that you should let terrible behavior slide and not hold abusers accountable in any way. I just want to be really clear that that is not at all what I’m suggesting or saying. What I’m suggesting is that we misunderstand what forgiveness means and what it is for. We think forgiveness means condoning or enabling bad behavior. And we think it is for the benefit of the person being forgiven. It is to let them know that what they did is okay and to free them of any burden they might carry as a result of their actions. I’m simply suggesting here that forgiveness might not actually be about condoning or signing off on bad behavior, and it might not be for the benefit of the person being forgiven. In fact, it might not be about that person at all. That person doesn’t even necessarily need to know that they’ve been forgiven. What I’m suggesting here is that forgiveness is a process undergone by the person who has been harmed in order to help them heal and move forward with their lives. It’s not about relieving the other person’s guilt or allowing them to think they didn’t do something wrong, it’s just about personally freeing yourself from the weight of resentment and bitterness. This also might not be a tool you find useful. You might feel like you are able to live free of resentment without undergoing a process of forgiveness. And that is absolutely your right, and your experience and I have no problem with that whatsoever. This is not me saying that forgiveness is the only path to freedom or peace or serenity. This is just a suggestion that it might be a useful tool for some when framed the way I framed it here in this caption and in the video. For the full conversation and context you can listen to episode 127 of my podcast feat. @whithertford

PLEASE READ BEFORE COMMENTING:
This is an excerpt from a full hour long episode about mental health where I speak at length about how frustrated I get when people offer me simple fixes for depression and anxiety. So if it sounds like I’m boiling the big, daunting, overwhelming topic of mental health down to something that’s simple and easily managed believe me I get how frustrating that is. I never want the solution to my poor mental health to be simple. I always want a very complex answer that is hard to grasp and harder to achieve. To me the problem is not simple so the answer can’t be. The problem resides in me. And I am not simple. I am complex and unknowable and multifaceted. So when someone tells me to drink some water and go for a run I want to scream at them for belittling my immense complexity and making it seem like I could so easily be understood. But here’s the rub… and this is just my experience, but the really annoying thing is that whenever I do something simple like drinking more water or going for a quick walk or working through a to-do list… it works. And I hate that. But it does. And that’s just me, but maybe it could be useful for you too, despite all your infinitely mysterious complexity. ♥️

On the day where I had the panic attack on set my legs were shaking so bad on the horse I could barely walk when they finally pulled me off. I was convinced I was going to be fired. And even if they didn’t fire me I was really considering the possibility that I might not be cut out for this line of work. That I might not have what it takes to do it at this level. I was humiliated in front of my colleagues and in front of lots of people I really respect. I didn’t know if I could bounce back. This thing really shook me to my core. That’s what I mean when I say the only thing I could do was keep showing up. I had no other tools, no other tricks, nothing else to fall back on. I stayed scared, I stayed embarrassed and unsure of myself, I stayed worried about my future in this profession, and just continued to show up anyway. Continued to meet my fear eye to eye with respect, bow to it, and then respectfully decline its invitation to turn and run. I don’t know the specifics of your situation. But I know what overwhelming and all-consuming fear feels like. And I truly believe that if I can find a route through it, then there’s a good chance you can find a way through whatever it is that’s scaring you. ♥️

Check out @ameliasamson for the OG vid. Few things: yes, I’m aware that the actual button has a bigger surface area than a pen clicker. Yes, I’m aware it has a larger internal shape and network of nerve endings than the pen clicker image would suggest. My entire point is that it’s a lot more complicated than a simple button you press/switch on or off. So when you comment that it’s actually more complicated than a pen clicker you are agreeing with my point. I could have easily made this video five times as long if I wanted to get into all of the different ways I’ve been taught by different partners over the years to effectively “push the button”. And lastly believe me, your personal preferences are not universal. So you might think, “what’s he talking about? All you have to do is (insert your personal preference here) what’s so hard about that?” It’s not hard necessarily, and I do believe that people should be communicating and putting forth the effort. My point is it’s not just as basic as locating a light switch and flicking it on or off. This really shouldn’t be controversial.
